03715nam a22004575i 9780226044545DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102007ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260445457 a10.7208/97802260445452doi  a(DE-B1597)523933  a(OCoLC)781300294  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aMUS0000002bisacsh1 aFeldman, Martha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOpera and Sovereignty :bTransforming Myths in Eighteenth-Century Italy /cMartha Feldman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (584 p.) :b4 color plates, 46 halftones, 26 musical examples, 10 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tEditorial Principles -- t1. Evenings at the Opera -- t2. Arias: Form, Feeling, Exchange -- t3. Programming Nature, Parma, 1759: First Case Study -- t4. Festivity and Time -- t5. Abandonments in a Theater State, Naples, 1764: Second Case Study -- t6. Myths of Sovereignty -- t7. Bourgeois Theatrics, Perugia, 1781: Third Case Study -- t8. Morals and Malcontents -- t9. Death of the Sovereign, Venice, 1797: Fourth Case Study -- tEpilogue -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerformed throughout Europe during the 1700s, Italian heroic opera, or opera seria, was the century’s most significant musical art form, profoundly engaging such figures as Handel, Haydn, and Mozart. Opera and Sovereignty is the first book to address this genre as cultural history, arguing that eighteenth-century opera seria must be understood in light of the period’s social and political upheavals. Taking an anthropological approach to European music that’s as bold as it is unusual, Martha Feldman traces Italian opera’s shift from a mythical assertion of sovereignty, with its festive forms and rituals, to a dramatic vehicle that increasingly questioned absolute ideals. She situates these transformations against the backdrop of eighteenth-century Italian culture to show how opera seria both reflected and affected the struggles of rulers to maintain sovereignty in the face of a growing public sphere. In so doing, Feldman explains why the form had such great international success and how audience experiences of the period differed from ours today. Ambitiously interdisciplinary, Opera and Sovereignty will appeal not only to scholars of music and anthropology, but also to those interested in theater, dance, and the history of the Enlightenment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226044545423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226044545.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles